{{Solar terms}}
The traditional East Asian calendars divide a year into 24 [[solar term]]s. '''''Báilù''''', ''Hakuro'', ''Baengno'', or ''Bạch lộ'' ({{CJKV|t=白露|s=白露|p=báilù|j=白露|r=hakuro|k=백로|rr=baengno|v=bạch lộ|l=white dew}}) is the 15th solar term. It begins when the Sun reaches the [[celestial longitude]] of 165° and ends when it reaches the longitude of 180°. It more often refers in particular to the day when the Sun is exactly at the celestial longitude of 165°. In the [[Gregorian calendar]], it usually begins around September 7 and ends around September 23. [[Mid-Autumn Festival]] is celebrated around this time.
